FIG. 1. Nuclear translocation of NF‐B. (A) Translocation of the dimeric transcription factor NF‐B was monitored by immunostaining for the p65 subunit. (B) HUVECs were stimulated with TNF as described in the text. To detect distribution of the transcription factor, cells were ﬁxed and permeabilized and then incubated with a monoclonal antibody against the p65 subunit of the NF‐B transcription factor and secondary antimouse IgG antibodies coupled to Alexa Fluor 647. Images of nonstimulated (left) and TNF‐stimulated (right) cells.

IL‐1 and TNFa Use Different Receptors to Induce NF‐kB Translocation The cytokines IL‐1 and TNF activate different receptors and different upstream arms of the proinﬂammatory pathway to induce NF‐B translocation (Fig. 3). To prove the speciﬁcity and thereby the biological relevance of our assay, we used siRNA technology to demonstrate that the two different cytokines use their natural, physiologically relevant receptors to activate NF‐B. The sequence selection of small double‐stranded siRNAs used in these experiments was as described previously (Jagla et al., 2005). Speciﬁc knockdown of the receptor for TFN (TNFR1), by transfecting cells with speciﬁc siRNAs 48 h before stimulation, signiﬁcantly reduced NF‐B translocation in response to TFN. In contrast, knockdown of the TNF receptor did not affect IL‐1‐stimulated NF‐B translocation. NF‐kB Translocation Depends on IkB Kinase (IKK) and Proteasome Activity We tested the effects of three drugs: curcumin, sulindac sulﬁde, and RO106–9920. Both curcumin and sulindac target the IKK complex, which

