E‐Selectin Expression Has Multiple Activators Stimulation with IL‐1 (Fig. 6B) results in a similar dose–response curve to that which is observed following stimulation with TNF (Fig. 6A). A minimal response (5% positive cells) is observed after stimulation with a low cytokine concentration (30 ng/ml). This response increases with dose and plateaus at 50% positive cells following stimulation with 1 g/ml IL‐1. CD40L and LPS are also effective inducers of E‐selectin expression but they are less potent than either TNF or IL‐1. The dose–response relationships for CD40L and LPS are shown in Fig. 6C and D, respectively. In both cases, a smaller response is achieved than with cytokine stimulation; a maximum of 8% positive cells for CD40L and of 15% for LPS. Expression of E‐selectin is dependent on IKK and proteasome activity, as demonstrated by the inhibitory effect of curcumin and RO106–9920 (Fig. 7). Statistical analysis revealed a Z0 value of 0.77 for activation of the assay with TNF.

